The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Guwahati, Jan. 2: Four elephants were mowed down by a goods train in Karbi Anglong district today.           
	Abhijit Rabha, the conservator of forests (wildlife) in the district, said a herd moving towards a reserve forest, was crossing the tracks when the train mowed them down around 2am. The animals, entangled in the front-guard and undercarriage of the engine, were dragged for nearly a kilometre.                  
	 Chandigarh (PTI): A probe team on Saturday questioned the principal of the school that had expelled Ruchika Girhotra. The team is said to have sought accounts books and the attendance register because the school claims Ruchika was expelled because she did not pay her fees for six months from April 1990.                   
	 Balrampur (PTI): An alert has been sounded along the Indo- Nepal border following reports that terrorists had infiltrated into Bihar from the neighbouring country, officials said.                   
	Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): Leading space scientists of the world will deliberate on key areas of research at a space summit here as part of the 97th Indian Science Congress to be inaugurated by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh on Sunday.                  
	New Delhi (PTI): A Sikh community group has accused the CBI and the Centre of mishandling the 1984 riot cases. The All India Sikh Conference (Babbar) said the government granted sanction to the CBI to chargesheet Congress leader Sajjan Kumar but did not mention the other people involved.                  
	 Bangalore (PTI): A Nepal-origin thief wanted in a murder case was shot at after he stabbed a police inspector who tried to arrest him. Namraz Thapa Bahadur stabbed police inspector Mohammad Rafi. Doctors said both were out of danger.                                                                                                                                              
